What is Matplotlib?¶

Matplotlib¶

  • A popular plotting library in Python.
  • Provides a set of drawing APIs through the pyplot module, and hides the complex structure composed of many drawing objects within this set of APIs.
  • Different from other drawing software, we draw through programming!

To install (https://matplotlib.org/users/installing.html):¶

  • Use Anacondas GUI
  • With Conda: conda install matplotlib
  • With PyPl (Python Package Index): pip install -U matplotlib

Reference:¶

  • Examples: https://matplotlib.org/gallery/index.html
  • User guide: https://matplotlib.org/tutorials/index.html

Why Matplotlib?¶

  • Good for data visualization

    • E.g., the "Charts" function in MS Excel

  • Very powerful and flexible

    • Professional quality
    • Fully controlled by the programmer

  • Platform independent

    • Windows, Linux, MacOS
    • Can export as many image types

  • Many online free examples

    • https://matplotlib.org/gallery/index.html
In [2]:
import matplotlib as mlt
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

Examples¶

Creating 100 data points in [0, 10]. Remark: the NumPy function np.linspace(start, stop, num) returns a one-dimensional ndarray with num evenly spaced samples over the interval [start, stop].

plt.plot(x, np.sin(x)) # draw a sin curve

Basic Concept: Figure and Axes¶

A Figure is the object that contains your figure. An Axis is an object of a bounding box with x-axis and y-axis. We can draw on an Axes.

A figure with multi-axes¶

In [ ]:
fig = plt.figure() # create an empty Figure
ax1 = plt.axes() # create an Axes for the Figure
ax2 = fig.add_axes([0.5, 0.5, 0.2, 0.2]) # add another Axes

Components of a Figure¶

Line Plot (OO Style)¶

Now, let's try to draw a curve y = sin(x), where 0 <= x <= 10

Solution: Sample 1000 points in [0,10], calculate y = sin(x) for these 1000 points, and then join these (x,y) points by line segments. This is called line plot.

In [45]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 1000) # 1000 points
ax.plot(x, np.sin(x))
Out[45]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7fbe5ce3ba20>]

10 points

ax.plot(x, np.sin(x))

Styling Line Plot: Line Color¶

Changing line colors

In [12]:
# line colors 
fig = plt.figure()
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 0), color='blue') # specify color by name
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 1), color='g') # short color code (rgbcmyk)
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 2), color='0.75') # Grayscale between 0 and 1
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 3), color='#FFDD44') # Hex code (RRGGBB from 00 to FF)
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x - 4), color=(1.0, 0.2, 0.3)) # RGB tuple, values 0 and 1
Out[12]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7fbe5e85a5f8>]

Styling Line Plot: Line Style¶

changing line styles

In [13]:
fig = plt.figure()
plt.plot(x, x + 0, linestyle='solid')
plt.plot(x, x + 1, linestyle='dashed')
plt.plot(x, x + 2, linestyle='dashdot')
plt.plot(x, x + 3, linestyle='dotted')
# For short, you can use the following codes:
plt.plot(x, x + 4, linestyle='-') # solid
plt.plot(x, x + 5, linestyle='--') # dashed
plt.plot(x, x + 6, linestyle='-.') # dashdot
plt.plot(x, x + 7, linestyle=':'); # dotted

Remark If no color is specified, Matplotlib will automatically cycle through a set of default colors fro multiple lines.

Styling Line Plot: Label¶

A figure can have many kinds of labels

  • figure title: plt.title()
  • axis labels: plt.xlabel(), plt.ylabel()
  • legends: plt.legend()
In [16]:
# Labeling Plots
fig = plt.figure()
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 1000)
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x))
plt.title('A Since Curve')
plt.xlabel('x')
plt.ylabel('sin(x)')
Out[16]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'sin(x)')

Styling Line Plot: Simple Legend¶

In [ ]:
fig = plt.figure()
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 1000)

To draw the legend, we can specify the label of each line using the label keyword of the plot() function. '-g' and ':b' are both handy combination of line style & color

In [17]:
plt.plot(x, np.sin(x), '-g', label='sin(x)')
plt.plot(x, np.cos(x), ':b', label='cos(x)')
plt.legend()
Out[17]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7fbe5e254588>

MATLAB Style vs. Object-Oriented Style¶

Previously we are using MATLAB style. You can also try the object-oriented style, i.e., plot through Axes object.

  • plt.plot() ax.plot()
  • plt.legend() ax.legend()
  • plt.xlabel() ax.set_xlabel()
  • plt.ylabel() ax.set_ylabel()
  • plt.xlim() ax.set_xlim()
  • plt.ylim() ax.set_ylim()
  • plt.title() ax.set_title()

The Axes object has a powerful ax.set() function that can set everything: ax.set(xlim, ylim, xlable, ylabel, title)

  • ax.set(xlim, ylim, xlable, ylabel, title)
In [ ]:
# Object-oriented Style
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 1000)
ax.plot(x, np.sin(x))
ax.set(xlim=(0, 10), ylim=(-2, 2), xlabel='x', ylabel='sin(x)', title='A Simple Plot')

Annotating a Plot¶

Ref: https://matplotlib.org/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.axes.Axes.annotate.html

In [ ]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
t = np.arange(0.0, 5.0, 0.01)
s = np.cos(2*np.pi*t)
ax.plot(t, s, lw=2)
ax.annotate('local max', xy=(2, 1), xytext=(3, 1.5), arrowprops=dict(facecolor='black', shrink=0.05))
ax.set_ylim(-2, 2)
  • xy specifies the location of the annotation;
  • xytext specifies the location of the text;
  • arrowprops specifies the arrow between xytext and xy.

Scatter plots¶

In a scatter plot, the data points are represented individually with a dot or circle or other shape. In Matplotlib, we can draw scatter plots using either plt.plot() or plt.scatter().

In [49]:
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 30)
y = np.sin(x)
plt.plot(x, y, 'o', color='black', markersize=20)
Out[49]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7fbe5ca47278>]

The parameter 'o' tells plot() to draw a scatter instead of line. It represents the type of symbol used for the data point. Another optional parameter markersize controls the size of the marker.

More Symbols for Scatter Plots¶

In [50]:
rng = np.random.RandomState(0)
for marker in ['o', '.', ',', 'x', '+', 'v', '^', '<', '>', 's', 'd']:
    plt.plot(rng.rand(5), rng.rand(5), marker, label="marker='{0}'".format(marker))
plt.legend(numpoints=1)
plt.xlim(0, 1.8)
Out[50]:
(0, 1.8)
  • rng.rand(5) returns a list of 5 random numbers.
  • the numpoints=1 in legend() means that only 1 symbol is shown in each legend

Scatter plots with plt.scatter()¶

On the one hand, plt.scatter() can be used in a similar way to plt.plot(). On the other hand, plt.scatter() allows to control each individual point (size, color, etc.). It is more powerful, but could be slower if you have huge amount of points to plot.

In [51]:
x = np.linspace(0, 10, 30)
y = np.sin(x)
plt.scatter(x, y, marker='o', color='red')
Out[51]:
<matplotlib.collections.PathCollection at 0x7fbe5d4e09e8>

Scatter Plots: Plot 100 random points with random sizes and colors¶

In [52]:
rng = np.random.RandomState(0)
x, y, colors, sizes = rng.randn(100), rng.randn(100), rng.rand(100), 1000 * rng.rand(100)
plt.scatter(x, y, c=colors, s=sizes, alpha=0.3,cmap='viridis')
plt.colorbar() # show color scale
Out[52]:
<matplotlib.colorbar.Colorbar at 0x7fbe5dab0d30>
  1. rng.randn(100) returns a list of 100 random numbers with standard normal distribution; while rng.rand(100) returns a list of 100 random numbers in [0, 1].
  2. In plt.scatter(), parameters c and s can set the color and size of each individual point.
  3. cmap: colormap, defines how to map a value to a color.
  4. alpha=0.3 makes the circles transparent.

More about colormap in Matplotlib: https://matplotlib.org/3.2.0/tutorials/colors/colormaps.html

Object-Oriented Style: axes.scatter()¶

Ref: https://matplotlib.org/3.1.1/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.axes.Axes.scatter.html

In [37]:
np.random.seed(19680801)
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
for color in ['blue', 'orange', 'green']:
    n = 750
    x, y = np.random.rand(2, n)
    scale = 200.0 * np.random.rand(n)
    ax.scatter(x, y, s=scale, c=color, label=color, alpha=0.3, edgecolors='none')
ax.legend()
ax.grid(True)
  1. x, y = np.random.rand(2, n) returns two sequences to x and y, each with n random numbers.
  2. ax.grid(True) show the grid lines.

Grouped Bar Chart with Axes.bar()¶

labels, men_means, women_means = ['G1', 'G2', 'G3', 'G4', 'G5'], [20, 34, 30, 35, 27], [25, 32, 34, 20, 25]
x = np.arange(len(labels))  # the label locations
width = 0.35  # the width of the bars
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
rects1 = ax.bar(x - width/2, men_means, width, label='Men')
rects2 = ax.bar(x + width/2, women_means, width, label='Women')
# Add some text for labels, title and custom x-axis tick labels, etc.

ax.set_title('Scores by group and gender')

ax.set_xticklabels(labels)
ax.legend()

Visualizing Errors¶

In many applications, we need to report a measurement with augmented uncertainties. E.g., 802 (km/s), 651 kg, etc. When visualizing the results, showing the errors can convey more complete information. Next, we show an example of plotting a scatter figure with error bars.

Plot Error Bars by plt.errorbar()¶

In [55]:
x, dy = np.linspace(0, 10, 50), 0.8
y = np.sin(x) + dy * np.random.randn(50) # introduce random errors to y = np.sin(x)
plt.errorbar(x, y, yerr=dy, fmt='.k')
Out[55]:
<ErrorbarContainer object of 3 artists>
  1. In plt.errorbar(), parameters yerr sets the errorbar size (which can be a scalar or an array); fmt sets the format of the data points in a similar way to plt.plot(). 'k' 'black'.
  2. For more details, check the reference at https://matplotlib.org/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.errorbar.html

Multiple Subplots in a Figure¶

Sometimes we need to include multiple Axes (or called subplots) in a single Figure. There are several ways to do that.

  • plt.axes()
  • Figure.add_axes()
  • plt.subplot()
  • plt.subplots()
  • plt.GridSpec()

In [66]:
# Subplots by Hand: plt.axes()

# plt.axes() takes an optional argument that is a list of four numbers 
#   [bottom, left, width, height] in the figure coordinate system, 
#   which range from 0 at the bottom left of the figure
#                 to 1 at the top right of the figure

ax1 = plt.axes() # standard axes
ax2 = plt.axes([0.6, 0.6, 0.2, 0.2])
ax3 = plt.axes([0.2, 0.2, 0.4, 0.2])

# plt.axes() is equivalent to the object-oriented style figure.add_axes().
In [67]:
# Subplots by Hand: Figure.add_axes()

fig = plt.figure()
ax1 = fig.add_axes([0.1, 0.5, 0.8, 0.4], xticklabels=[], ylim=(-1.2, 1.2))
ax2 = fig.add_axes([0.1, 0.1, 0.8, 0.4], ylim=(-1.2, 1.2))
x = np.linspace(0, 10)
ax1.plot(np.sin(x))
ax2.plot(np.cos(x))

# Remark:
# We need to set the size and location carefully to make the two subplots well aligned
# E.g., the y-coordinate of ax1 (i.e., 0.5) is equal to the y-coordinate of
# ax2 (i.e., 0.1) + the height of ax2 (i.e., 0.4).
Out[67]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7fbe5c07dc18>]

Plot a Grid of Subplots with plt.subplot()¶

It's a common pattern to organize the subplots as a grid. plt.subplot() takes three arguments: # of rows, # of columns, and the index of the plot to be created The index begins with 1 and runs from the upper left to the bottom right

In [68]:
# Plot a Grid of Subplots with plt.subplot()

fig = plt.figure()
for i in range(1, 7):
    plt.subplot(2, 3, i)
    plt.text(0.5, 0.5, str((2, 3, i)), fontsize=18, ha='center')
    
# Remark:
# plt.text() can show a text in the current Axes. The argument ha refers to
#   horizontalalignment.

# BUT problem is:
#    the subplots are too crowded!
In [69]:
# plt.subplots_adjust() can be used to adjust the spacing between these plots.
# The hspace and wspace arguments specify the spacing along the height and 
#    width of the figure, in units of the subplot size.

fig = plt.figure()
fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4, wspace=0.4)
for i in range(1, 7):
    ax = fig.add_subplot(2, 3, i)
    ax.text(0.5, 0.5, str((2, 3, i)), fontsize=18, ha='center')
    
# BUT problem is:
#    plotting the subplots one by one is two tedious!
In [70]:
# Plot a Grid of Subplots with plt.subplots()
# Ref: https://matplotlib.org/3.2.0/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.subplots.html
# plt.subplots() creates a full grid of subplots in a single line, returning 
#    a Figure object and an array of Axes objects

fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 3, sharex='col', sharey='row')
for i in range(2):
    for j in range(3):
        ax[i, j].text(0.5, 0.5, str((i, j)), fontsize=18, ha='center')
        
# Remark:
# The first two arguments specify the number of rows and the number of 
#    columns of the grid, respectively.
# sharex = 'col' means sharing the x tick labelsfor each column.
# sharey = 'row' means sharing the y tick labelsfor each row.

Plot Multiple Subplots with plt.GridSpec() and plt.subplot()¶

Problem: When we use plt.subplots(), all plots have the same size. But sometimes we want to be more flexible.

plt.GridSpec() will "cut" a Figure into a grid of blocks, and then allow plt.subplot() to generate an Axes on top of multiple blocks.

In [71]:
# Plot Multiple Subplots with plt.GridSpec() and plt.subplot()
# Ref: https://matplotlib.org/3.1.1/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.gridspec.GridSpec.html

grid = plt.GridSpec(2, 3, wspace=0.4, hspace=0.3)
plt.subplot(grid[0, 0])
plt.subplot(grid[0, 1:])
plt.subplot(grid[1, :2])
plt.subplot(grid[1, 2])
Out[71]:

# Plot Multiple Subplots with plt.GridSpec() and Axes.add_subplot()

def f(t):
    return np.exp(-t) * np.cos(2*np.pi*t)

t1 = np.arange(0.0, 3.0, 0.01)

fig = plt.figure()
grid = plt.GridSpec(2, 2, wspace=0.4, hspace=0.3)
ax1 = fig.add_subplot(grid[1, :])
ax1.margins(0.05)           # Default margin is 0.05, value 0 means fit
ax1.plot(t1, f(t1))

ax2 = fig.add_subplot(grid[0, 0])
ax2.margins(2, 2)           # Values >0.0 zoom out
ax2.plot(t1, f(t1))
ax2.set_title('Zoomed out')

ax3 = fig.add_subplot(grid[0, 1])
ax3.margins(x=0, y=-0.25)   # Values in (-0.5, 0.0) zooms in to center
ax3.plot(t1, f(t1))
ax3.set_title('Zoomed in')
Out[72]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Zoomed in')
